Data Tranformation

turkey$Houses.Ruined <-turkey$Houses.Destroyed + turkey$Houses.Damaged
turkey$Affected <-turkey$Directly.affected + turkey$Indirectly.Affected

# while working we observed that there were an unexpected error 19 values for turkey became na because of high value so we introduce a new value
# Example threshold to differentiate between large and small values
threshold <- 1e9  # Adjust this threshold as needed based on your data characteristics

# Initialize an empty vector to store the calculated values
turkey$Monetary.LossUSD <- numeric(nrow(turkey))

# Loop through each row and perform the calculation based on value size
for (i in 1:nrow(turkey)) {
  if (turkey$Losses..Local[i] >= threshold) {
    # For large values, scale down before calculation
    turkey$Monetary.LossUSD[i] <- turkey$Losses..USD[i] + (turkey$Losses..Local[i] / threshold) * 0.035
  } else {
    # For small values, perform the calculation without scaling
    turkey$Monetary.LossUSD[i] <- turkey$Losses..USD[i] + turkey$Losses..Local[i] * 0.035
  }
}

# Convert to integer (if necessary)
turkey$Monetary.LossUSD <- as.integer(turkey$Monetary.LossUSD)

Feature Addition 1

mean_deaths <- mean(turkey$Deaths)
calculate_severity <- function(deaths, mean_deaths)
  {
  if (deaths > mean_deaths) 
    {
    severity <- 1 + 9 * ((deaths - mean_deaths) / max(turkey$Deaths - mean_deaths, na.rm = TRUE))
  } 
  else if (deaths < mean_deaths) {
    severity <- 1 + 9 * ((deaths - mean_deaths) / min(turkey$Deaths - mean_deaths, na.rm = TRUE))
  } else {
    severity <- 5
  }
  return(round(severity))
}

# Apply the function to create the Event_Severity column
turkey$Event_Severity <- as.integer(sapply(turkey$Deaths, calculate_severity, mean_deaths))

  mutate(

VIF

# List of y variables
y_variables <- c("Year","DataCards","Deaths", "Monetary.LossUSD", "Event_Severity", "Houses.Ruined", "Affected","Event_factor")

# Loop through each y variable
for (y_var in y_variables) {
  # Create formula for the regression model
  formula <- as.formula(paste("turkey_c$", y_var, "~ turkey_c$Year+ turkey_c$DataCards+turkey_c$DataCards+turkey_c$Deaths + turkey_c$Monetary.LossUSD + turkey_c$Event_Severity + turkey_c$Houses.Ruined + turkey_c$Affected+ turkey_c$Event_factor"))

  # Fit linear regression model
  model <- lm(formula, data = turkey_c)

  # Check for multicollinearity using VIF
  vif_result <- car::vif(model)

  # Print VIF results for each y variable
  cat("VIF results for", y_var, ":\n")
  print(vif_result)
  cat("\n")
}

for (y_var in y_variables) {
  # Create formula for the regression model
  formula <- as.formula(paste("pakistan_c$", y_var, "~ pakistan_c$Year +pakistan_c$DataCards+ pakistan_c$Deaths +  pakistan_c$Event_Severity + pakistan_c$Houses.Ruined + pakistan_c$Affected+ pakistan_c$Event_factor"))

  # Fit linear regression model
  model <- lm(formula, data = pakistan_c)

  # Check for multicollinearity using VIF
  vif_result <- car::vif(model)

  # Print VIF results for each y variable
  cat("VIF results for", y_var, ":\n")
  print(vif_result)
  cat("\n")

y_train <- train_data$Deaths

# Standardizing the predictors
X_train_std <- scale(X_train)
X_test_std <- scale(X_test)

# Fit the elastic net model

enet_model_turkey <- cv.glmnet(X_train_std, y_train, alpha = 0.5)  # alpha = 0.5 indicates the elastic net

best_lambda <- enet_model_turkey$lambda.min

# Make predictions on the test set
y_pred <- predict(enet_model_turkey, newx = X_test_std, s = best_lambda)

# Evaluate the model
mse <- mean((y_pred - y_test)^2)
rsquared <- cor(y_pred, y_test)^2

cat("Best Lambda:", best_lambda, "\n")
## Best Lambda: 5.106478

cat("R-squared:", rsquared, "\n")

abline(0, 1, col = "red")  # Adding a line for perfect prediction

#View the distribution of the newly created classification
#table(country_c$Severity_Class)

turkey_c$Severity_Class <- ifelse(turkey_c$Event_Severity >= 5, "High Severity", "Low Severity")

# Define the quartiles of the 'Year' column to split into temporal categories
year_quantiles <- quantile(turkey_c$Year, probs = c(0, 1/3, 2/3, 1))

# Classify based on quartiles of 'Year'
turkey_c$Temporal_Class <- cut(turkey_c$Year,
                                  breaks = year_quantiles,
                                  labels = c("Early Period", "Mid Period", "Recent Period"),
                                  include.lowest = TRUE)

classify_disaster <- function(severity, impact, cluster) {
  risk_level <- character(length = length(severity))
  
 for (i in 1:length(severity)) {
    if (severity[i] == "High Severity") {
      if (impact[i] == "Severe Impact") {
        risk_level[i] <- "Very High Risk"
      } else if (impact[i] == "Moderate Impact") {
        risk_level[i] <- "High-Moderate Risk"
      } else {
        risk_level[i] <- "High-Low Risk"
      }
    } else if (severity[i] != "High Severity" && impact[i] == "Severe Impact") {
      risk_level[i] <- "High Risk"
    } else if (cluster[i] == "Most DataCards") {
      risk_level[i] <- "Clustered Risk"
    } else {
      risk_level[i] <- "Undefined Risk"
    }
  }
  
  return(risk_level)
}

combined_data_asia_1$Disaster_Risk <- classify_disaster(
  combined_data_asia_1$Severity_Class,
  combined_data_asia_1$Impact_Class,
  combined_data_asia_1$cluster_id
)
# Ensure 'Year' is a factor for clearer visualization
combined_data_asia_1$Year <- as.factor(combined_data_asia_1$Temporal_Class)

# Create the heatmap
heatmap <- ggplot(combined_data_asia_1, aes(x = Year, y = Country, fill = Disaster_Risk)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(
    "Very High Risk" = "red",
    "High-Moderate Risk" = "orange",
    "High-Low Risk" = "yellow",
    "High Risk" = "yellowgreen",
    "Clustered Risk" = "skyblue",
    "Undefined Risk" = "grey"
  )) +
  labs(
    title = "Disaster Risk Heatmap",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Country",
    fill = "Disaster Risk"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

# Show the heatmap
print(heatmap)
